WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.480
So there's a whole bunch of different inputs and outputs. And actually, let me open this up,

00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:15.920
open up this in another tab. I'll just open up there because there are many examples for the

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:21.600
different inputs and outputs. So here we have inputs. So what we saw before was the slider

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:26.440
input. And if you click on this over here, you'll see a really basic example of that.

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:30.080
But there's also a text input. So I can enter text here, say,

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:39.040
Hello Shiny. And this example app will show how to use that. There's a numeric input.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:46.119
So it's similar to the text input, but uses a number input and you can, there's little arrows

00:00:46.119 --> 00:00:53.200
on it. Checkbox input, checkbox input, which you can just turn on and off by checking it,

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:58.320
or sorry, by clicking on it. And there's a whole bunch of other ones. So there's groups of check

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:10.400
boxes. There's radio buttons. There's a select input that has a dropdown box and dates and date

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:19.480
ranges. So these are the built-in inputs for Shiny. With all these inputs, they all sort of have a

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:25.400
common format where you say UI dot input something. And then the first thing that it's

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:31.480
going to have here, the first argument that it takes is an ID and then a label for it. And then

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:36.639
there's typically other parameters as well. So in this case, we're not using any of the other

00:01:36.639 --> 00:01:43.639
parameters, but so if we go to the slider input, it'll have, you have to set the minimum and

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:49.639
maximum value for the slider, as well as like, as well as the starting value. One thing that you

00:01:49.639 --> 00:01:54.760
can do with these is if you have an idea of what, of the kind of components that you want to add to

00:01:54.760 --> 00:02:01.959
your application is, you know, let's say we're working on this application here and we want to

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:08.039
add like a checkbox to it. So like if we want to be able to negate the value, so I can say,

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:12.600
we'll put a comma there just because that will help this auto-completion. I can say UI dot input

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:23.320
underscore checkbox, and then parens, and then I can give it a name like negate and negate

00:02:24.039 --> 00:02:30.199
slider value. I'll call it, use that as a label. And I can click on this button and it will,

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:35.960
it will provide this checkbox, which right now doesn't do anything. We need to actually use it

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:44.759
in our application. So let's see. So let's say, how would we do this here? So we say, we say if

00:02:47.080 --> 00:03:00.919
input dot negate, then I'll call this multiplier equals negative one, else

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:08.279
multiplier, multiplier equals one. All right, and then I can put this here.

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:21.880
And if I rerun this, then this will work here. Now I didn't actually fix the texture with this

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:27.800
n times two, but, but you can see how this works that just simply, you know, clicking on this will

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:35.240
cause this code to re-execute, and this, this value will be updated. And, and again, you know,

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:40.279
if we, there's other types of inputs that we want to use, we can just refer to this examples page.

00:03:40.279 --> 00:03:46.759
Here I'm in another browser tab, and I can just look for different types of inputs to use.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:03:58.300
Thank you.

